The paper deals with evaluating reading comprehension systems, which falls under the category of natural language processing (NLP). Therefore, cs.CL (Computation and Language) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also proposes an adversarial evaluation scheme, which involves testing the ability of models to handle unexpected inputs, which is a common theme in the field of machine learning and artificial intelligence (AI), making cs.AI the second likely sub-category. The paper also uses machine learning models, which falls under the category of machine learning (cs.LG) and neural networks (cs.NE). Finally, the paper uses the Stanford Question Answering Dataset (SQuAD), which involves processing text and images, making cs.CV a possible sub-category as well.
